<DOC><DOCNO> AP880829-0226 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-88 0906EDT</FILEID><FIRST>a a BC-SPE--HealthCare:ExercisePoll     08-29 0161</FIRST><SECOND>BC-SPE--Health Care: Exercise Poll,0161</SECOND><HEAD>BC-SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD><HEAD>Health Care: Exercise Poll</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Americans say they exercise an average of 8.7hours a week, but a majority believe they don't exercise enough,according to results of a nationwide poll.   The poll, conducted for Parents Magazine, also found that 47percent of Americans are satisfied with their weight, 46 percentsaid they are overweight and 6 percent said they are too thin.   Fifty-six percent of those surveyed said they don't exerciseenough; 43 percent said they do.   The most popular exercise, reported by 64 percent of the peoplewho said they exercise, was walking rapidly. Forty-six percent saidthey follow some exercise program of their own, 44 percent ride abicycle, 39 percent swim, and 32 percent play a sport.   The magazine said its polling firm, Kane, Parsons andamp; Associates,surveyed 1,006 adults selected at random by telephone. The poll'smargin of error is plus or minus 3 percent.</TEXT></DOC>